ce:section.ce:para:
The sorption properties of materials were measured using a fully automated Sieverts hydrogen titration instrument (Fig. 3
). A detailed description of this experimental technique is available in [13]. The annealed samples were crushed in the glove box (under argon atmosphere) just before insertion into high-pressure sample cell and connected to the apparatus. Before starting activation experiment, the samples were outgassed for at least 1h at a vacuum pressure of 1×10−3
mbar. The mass of studied samples is usually 1g. The hydrogen sorption rates were metered by a Brooks mass flow rate controller. The samples were then activated at a hydrogen pressure of 25atm and ambient temperature. The activation step eliminates surface barriers for hydrogen penetration and it prepares the alloy for repeated uses, to rapidly take up and release hydrogen. Finally, to complete the activation process, the alloys are also cycled.
